{
  "doc_id": "9228",
  "text": "In addition, in the tool domain it has become increasingly clear that action is a core semantic feature. Our prior work suggests that tool action similarity takes into account aspects of action appearance that include magnitude of arm movement and posture of the hand [CITATION_1] , and it is likely that additional features may determine which tools are close in neighborhood space. fMRI experiments in neurotypical adults have reported that tool-related actions may be represented with respect to their visual appearance and motion [CITATION_2] , whether they are performed with a tool or the hands (Bracci, CavinaPratesi, Ietswaart, Caramazza, & Peelen, 2012; [CITATION_3] , as well as such non-sensory features as the number of sequences they entail [CITATION_4] or their abstract function or goal [CITATION_5] ; for review, see [CITATION_6] . In future work it will be useful to characterize these and other features in the same tools to explore whether the neighborhood similarity space in the tool action domain is multi-dimensional.",
